Below is a **single‑file, self‑contained C binding** for the hot‑path “walk every block” iterator that BlockSci already provides in C++.  
It is deliberately tiny – only the symbols a C user needs are exported – but it still gives you a clean, zero‑overhead way to run a user‑supplied C callback on each block.

*The file contains both the public C header (`blocksci.h`) and the C++ implementation (`blocksci.cpp`).*  
You can drop the whole thing into your project, compile it as C++ (e.g. `g++ -std=c++20 -fPIC -shared blocksci.cpp -o libblocksci.so`) and then link the resulting shared library from any C program.

---

## 1. Public C header – `blocksci.h`

```c
/*=====================================================================
  blocksci.h – C binding for the BlockSci block iterator
  --------------------------------------------------------------------
  Goal:
    • Offer a tiny, “C‑friendly” API that lets a C program walk every
      block in the blockchain (≈800 M entries) and execute user code.
    • Keep the hot path as cheap as possible – the callback is invoked
      directly from the C++ iterator with no extra allocations.
    • Allow the user to stop the walk early and to carry opaque state.

  Usage (C):
        #include "blocksci.h"

        static int my_cb(void *ud, const bs_block_t *blk) {
            /* …do something cheap… */
            return 0;          // 0 → continue, non‑zero → abort walk
        }

        int main(void) {
            bs_iter_t *it = bs_iter_new();
            if (!it) return 1;
            bs_iter_foreach(it, my_cb, NULL);
            bs_iter_free(it);
        }
=====================================================================*/

#ifndef BLOCKSCI_H
#define BLOCKSCI_H

#ifdef __cplusplus
extern "C" {
#endif

/* Opaque iterator type – the C side never sees its definition. */
typedef struct bs_iter_s bs_iter_t;

/* A thin, POD description of a block that a C program can read.
   Only the fields that are cheap to copy are exposed; everything else
   stays inside the C++ world. */
typedef struct {
    uint64_t height;          /* Block height (0 = genesis)            */
    uint64_t timestamp;       /* Unix epoch seconds                    */
    uint64_t tx_count;        /* Number of transactions in the block   */
    const unsigned char *hash;/* 32‑byte SHA‑256 block hash (binary)   */
    const unsigned char *prev_hash; /* 32‑byte hash of the previous block */
} bs_block_t;

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Callback prototype.
   *user_data* is whatever the C caller passed to `bs_iter_foreach`.
   *blk* points to a read‑only `bs_block_t` that lives only for the
   duration of the callback – the implementation does **not** allocate
   memory for it.  Returning 0 tells the iterator to keep walking;
   any non‑zero value aborts the walk and propagates that value back
   to the caller.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
typedef int (*bs_block_cb_t)(void *user_data, const bs_block_t *blk);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Create / destroy an iterator that walks **all** blocks in the chain.
   The iterator holds a reference to the global BlockSci `Chain` object,
   so constructing it is cheap (no I/O, just a reference count bump).
   Returns NULL on fatal error (e.g. Chain not initialised).
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
bs_iter_t *bs_iter_new(void);

/* Release the iterator.  After this call the pointer must not be used. */
void bs_iter_free(bs_iter_t *it);

/* Walk the whole blockchain, invoking *cb* for each block.
   Returns:
        0   – walked all blocks without the callback ever aborting
        >0 – the callback returned a non‑zero value; that value is
             returned unchanged.
       -1   – iterator is NULL or an internal error occurred.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
int bs_iter_foreach(bs_iter_t *it, bs_block_cb_t cb, void *user_data);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   OPTIONAL: a “fast‑path” that lets the caller ask the iterator to stop
   after a given height.  If *max_height* is UINT64_MAX the walk is
   unlimited (the default behaviour of `bs_iter_foreach`).  This helper
   is cheap because it simply stores the limit inside the iterator.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
void bs_iter_set_max_height(bs_iter_t *it, uint64_t max_height);

#ifdef __cplusplus
}
#endif

#endif /* BLOCKSCI_H */
```

