## 4. Example C program (for documentation)

```c
/*=====================================================================
   example.c – demo of the BlockSci C binding
=====================================================================*/
#include "blocksci.h"
#include <stdio.h>
#include <inttypes.h>

static int print_block(void *ud, const bs_block_t *blk) {
    (void)ud;   // unused
    printf("height=%" PRIu64 "  time=%" PRIu64 "  txs=%" PRIu64 "\n",
           blk->height, blk->timestamp, blk->tx_count);
    /* Stop after the first 10 000 blocks – just to show early abort. */
    if (blk->height >= 9999) return 1;   // any non‑zero aborts the walk
    return 0;
}

int main(void) {
    bs_iter_t *it = bs_iter_new();
    if (!it) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Failed to initialise BlockSci iterator\n");
        return 1;
    }

    /* Optional: limit the walk to a maximum height (UINT64_MAX = no limit) */
    bs_iter_set_max_height(it, UINT64_MAX);

    int rc = bs_iter_foreach(it, print_block, NULL);
    if (rc != 0 && rc != 1) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Iteration stopped with error code %d\n", rc);
    }

    bs_iter_free(it);
    return 0;
}
```

Compile the example together with the library:

```bash
gcc -I. example.c -L. -lblocksci -lstdc++ -o example
```

Run it – you’ll see the first 10 000 block headers printed, then the walk aborts cleanly.

---

## 5. Performance checklist (why this is hot‑path ready)

| Concern                              | Design decision |
|--------------------------------------|-----------------|
| **Callback overhead**                | Direct C function pointer, no `std::function` or virtual dispatch. |
| **Memory allocation per block**      | None – a single stack‑allocated `bs_block_t` is reused. |
| **Cache friendliness**               | Only a few 8‑byte integers and two 32‑byte pointers per iteration. |
| **Branch prediction**                | The early‑out test (`height > max_h`) is a simple compare; the callback return test is a single integer branch. |
| **Thread safety**                    | Iterator is *not* thread‑safe (same as BlockSci).  The API is deliberately single‑threaded to keep the hot loop tight. |
| **Binary compatibility**             | The public header contains only POD types and opaque pointers; ABI is stable. |
| **Zero‑copy hash exposure**          | The `hash`/`prev_hash` fields are raw pointers into BlockSci’s internal buffers – no copy, but the C side must treat them as read‑only. |
| **Graceful abort**                   | Callback return value propagates instantly; no extra flag checks after the loop. |
| **Optional height limit**            | `bs_iter_set_max_height` stores a `uint64_t`; the limit is checked *inside* the loop without extra function calls. |

With these choices the per‑block cost is essentially the same as walking the original C++ iterator, plus the tiny cost of invoking a C function – exactly what high‑performance data‑frame libraries (Polars, pandas) do when they expose a “apply‑per‑row” API.

--- 

**That’s it!** Drop the two source files (`blocksci.h` + `blocksci.cpp`) into your build, compile the C++ side as a shared library, and you have a clean, low‑overhead C API for “run my code on every block”. Happy hacking!
